@NODE INTRO "Introduction"

@{JCENTER}@{b}User, meet NewView.  NewView, this is User.@{ub}


@{JLEFT}NewView is a program designed to allow the viewing of pictures
and animations exclusively through the use of Datatypes.

Features
  - shell support
  - ToolType support
  - multiselecting ASL-Requester (unless you've patched your requesters
    to something else [such as reqtools])
  - loading from and saving to clipboard
  - clipping and saving sections of pictures (cropping [can be very handy])
  - loading of next picture by pressing the Enter or the space key
  - can be used as a format converter (at present, provided you want to
    convert from anything else to IFF).
  - new ToolType for selecting screenmodes
  - saves files as RAW format, if the datatype will alow it
  - NewView will show only pictures or animations for which you have a 
    datatype

@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUIRE "Requirements"
@SMARTWRAP

@{JCENTER}@{b}And What Do We Need To Use This Thing???@{ub}



@{JLEFT}NewView should work on every Amiga running at least Kickstart 3.0.
It also requires a correctly installed Datatypes System.  This means that
the datatypes.library must be in (one of) your libs: assign(s), Commodore's
picture.datatype must be in SYS:Classes/DataTypes and datatypes for picture
formats such as ILBM, PNG, GIF, BitMap, etc. or anim, gif-anim, CDXL, etc.
must be properly installed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "Installation of NewView"
@SMARTWRAP
@{JCENTER}@{b}And Now For The REALLY HARD Bit@{ub}


@{JLEFT}Currently there is no installer script simply because there is no
need for one (this is, after all, an Amiga, not a Windoze machine and this
(NewView) is @{b}NOT@{ub} a complex program [yet]). To install NewView,
simply copy the NewView drawer to wherever you figure you stand the best
chance of remembering where you put it.  To further your chances of ever
being able to find it again, "@{b}LEAVE OUT@{ub}" its icon or drag it into
your WBStartup drawer.  In the latter case, NewView will thoughtfully
clutter up your Workbench with yet another cute little APPIcon if the
APPICON tooltype is activated.

@ENDNODE

@NODE USAGE "Usage"
@{JCENTER}@{b}And Now For How To Use This Little Puppy@{ub}


@{JLEFT}@{u}Starting from WB@{uu}

Upon starting NewView from the Workbench, an ASL-FileRequester will appear
(again, if you haven't replaced ASL with a req, reqtools, or etc. patch)
from which you may select the file(s) you want to view. If you select more 
than one file you could show the next by pressing Enter or Space key.
There are presently FIVE @{b}ToolTypes@{ub} available:

  CLIPBOARD:
    If you use this ToolType, the ASL-FileRequester will not appear at
    startup, provided there is at least part of a picture in the
    clipboard, which will be automatically loaded at startup.

  STARTDIR:
    Specifies the directory to which the file requester will initially
    point, maybe a directory containing your favourite pix.

  APPICON:
    If you use this ToolType, an appicon will be plunked down
    (initially, probably behind three windows and at least two other
    icons) somewhere on your already overcluttered WB.

  APPMENU:
    Similarly, if you use this ToolType, an appmenuentry will be
    added to the Workbench Tools menu.

  SCREENSELECT:
    By using this ToolType a ScreenModeRequester will be appear where you
    could select the screenmode you want. If you selected more than one 
    file a Requester will appear where you'll be asked if you want to see
    all files in the same screenmode. If you selected 'Yes' in the requester
    you could if you want a new screenmode press DEL. The ScreenModeRequester
    will appear by the next picture.


@{u}Starting from CLI@{uu}

NewView has a standard AmigaDOS template which looks like this:

 Path:NewView [FILE], [STARTDIR/K], [CLIPBOARD/S], [APPICON/S], [APPMENU/S]

With the entry FILE you may specify a file which will be loaded upon
startup in the absence of a CLIPBOARD entry.

CLIPBOARD, STARTDIR, APPICON, and APPMENU all work identically to their
ToolTypes counterparts as described above.  Remember that if you include
the keyword STARTDIR, you @{b}must@{ub} include a path name, for example:

  STARTDIR=RAM:MyTempGraphicsDrawer


@{u}ANIM Viewing@{uu}

Anims, naturally enough, are loaded in the same manner as are other
Graphics.  At present, while viewing an Anim, there are three keyboard
shortcuts available to you:

  P will start an anim in motion.
  S will stop it dead in its tracks.
  B will pause it ('til the cows come if that's important to you).
  E will play the anim endless, needs animation.datatype 41.4, could
         be found in the aminet/util/dtype/animation4105.lha
  + will show the next picture of the animation
  - will show the picture before


@{u}The Menu@{uu}

The Menu consists of two main entries, Project and Edit, with sub-entries.
All of the menu entries have keyboard shortcuts.

In the Project menu we have:

  Open (RAmiga-O):
    Selecting Open in the Project Menu will open the Multi-select File
    Requester from which you can select pictures to view.  Select more
    than one picture by holding a Shift key while selecting items with
    the left mouse-button.    
    Press the Return key to load the next picture.    

  Save As IFF (RAmiga-A):
    Selecting Save As allows you to save a picture to the path and
    filename of your choice. If you haven't selected an area within the
    picture, the whole picture will be saved. To select an area, see
    Select, below.

  Save As RAW (RAmiga-R):
    Selecting Save As allows you to save a picture to the path, filename
    and if the datatype alows it to save as the datatype format. If you
    haven't selected an area within the picture, the whole picture will
    be saved. To select an area, see Select, below. Also animations could
    be saved, if the datatype allows it.

  Print (RAmiga-P):
    Selecting Print will print the picture currently being viewed,
    using your Preferences Printer and settings.  A Requester will also
    appear allowing you to abort the print, if need be.     

  Info (RAmiga-I):
    Selecting Info will provide available information about the picture.

  Author (RAmiga-?):
    Selecting Author will get you some EXTREMELY IMPORTANT information
    about the program's copyright and so on, and so forth, and on and
    on, and so on, and etcetera, etc. You also get the information about
    translator for the language.

  Iconify (RAmiga-F):
    This will iconify NewView. By pressing the ApIcon twice the file you
    showed last will be loaded, by dragging another file on the Icon this
    file will be loaded.

  Quit (RAmiga-Q):
    Selecting Quit will get you OUTTATHEREREALDAMNEDFAST.


And in the Edit menu we have:

  Select (RAmiga-S):
    Selecting Select allows you to outline an area within your pic
    which can then be saved to the destination of your choice or copied
    to the clipboard. To select an area in your pic, select Select
    from the Edit menu, CLICK AND HOLD the left mouse button (LMB) at
    ANY corner of the desired area, then drag (a rubber-band box will
    follow you) the pointer to the diagonally opposite corner of the
    desired area. Let go of the LMB. The selected area will then
    change shades slightly (become hilighted) to indicate its bounds.
    If you got it wrong (messed up really badly), just select Deselect
    (Right Amiga-D) from the menu, and try it again (and again, and
    again, you'll get it yet). Doesn't work with animations.

  Deselect (RAmiga-D):
    If you select Deselect, any previously selected area will be
    deselected.

  Copy (RAmiga-C):
    Select Copy to copy the selected area (if one exists) or the whole
    picture to the clipboard.

  Clipboard (RAmiga-V):
    Select Clipboard to view whatever may be in the (you quessed it)
    clipboard.

@ENDNODE

